summary:
The Security Council:

Reaffirms its previous resolutions on Afghanistan, particularly 1386 (2001), 1510 (2003), 2011 (2011), 2041 (2012), 2069 (2012), and 2096 (2013);

Reaffirms its resolutions on terrorism, including 1267 (1999), 1368 (2001), 1373 (2001), and 2082 (2012);

Recalls its resolutions on the protection of civilians in armed conflict, women and peace and security, and children and armed conflict;

Reaffirms its commitment to Afghanistan's sovereignty, independence, territorial integrity, and national unity;

Recognizes the Afghan Authorities' responsibility for providing security and law and order;

Stresses the role of the International Security Assistance Force (ISAF) in assisting the Afghan Government to improve security and build its own security capabilities;

Underlines the importance of strengthening Afghan ownership and leadership in all fields of governance;

Welcomes the conclusions of the International Conference on Afghanistan in Bonn and the Tokyo Conference on Afghanistan;

Recognizes the interconnected nature of challenges in Afghanistan, including security, governance, human rights, rule of law, and development;

Stresses the need for further efforts by the Afghan Government to fight corruption and promote transparency;

Welcomes long-term commitments by international partners to support Afghanistan beyond transition;

Underlines the significance of the agreement to transfer full security responsibility to the Afghan Government by the end of 2014;

Acknowledges progress made and challenges remaining in security sector reform and governance.
The Security Council:

Welcomes the increased capacities and capabilities of the Afghan National Security Forces (ANSF), and stresses the need for Afghanistan and international donors to further strengthen the Afghan National Army and Police.

Urges continued professional training measures to ensure Afghan capability to assume increasing responsibilities and leadership of security operations, maintain public order, law enforcement, and protect the rights of Afghan citizens, particularly women and girls.

Welcomes the Chicago Summit Joint Declaration, which stresses the long-term commitment to lasting peace, security, and stability in Afghanistan beyond 2014.
